Reference for 9front rc(1): Plan 9 shell; syntax, variables, lists, I/O redirection, pipelines, built-in commands, functions, signal handlers, environment, invocation flags.

# 9front rc(1) — command language

## Synopsis

    rc [-srdiIlxebpvVr] [-c command] [-m initial] [file [arg ...]]

## Description

`rc` is the Plan 9 shell.  It executes commands read from a terminal, a file,
or (with `-c`) from the argument string.  Commands are separated by `;` or `&`
and terminated by a newline.  A command followed by `&` runs asynchronously;
its pid is stored in `$apid`.  After each foreground command finishes, `$status`
is set to its wait message (empty string means success).

A long command line may be continued on subsequent lines with a trailing `\`
followed by a newline; this sequence is treated as whitespace.  `\` is not
otherwise special in rc.

`#` begins a comment to end-of-line (except inside quotes).

## Simple commands

The first word of a simple command is looked up as:
1. An `rc` function or built-in command — executed by rc.
2. A name starting with `/` — used directly as the program path.
3. Anything else — searched in each directory in `$path`.

A script file is executable if it begins with `#!/bin/rc` (or another shell
path).  The first word of a simple command cannot be a keyword unless quoted.

**Keywords:** `for in while if not switch fn ~ ! @`

## Arguments and variables

**Unquoted word:** Any sequence of characters not including blank, tab,
newline, or `# ; & | ^ $ = \` ' { } ( ) < >`.

**Glob patterns:** An unquoted word containing `*`, `?`, or `[...]` is a
filename pattern.  `*` matches any sequence; `?` matches any single character;
`[class]` matches any character in the class (use `~` as first character to
complement).  Ranges `a-z` are supported.  `/` must appear explicitly; `.` and
`..` must appear at the start of a path component.  An unmatched pattern
stands for itself rather than expanding to empty.

**Quoted word:** Characters surrounded by single quotes `'...'`.  A literal
single quote inside is written as two consecutive single quotes `''`.

**List:** `(a b c)` — a list of arguments.  Variable values are lists.  Lists
have no recursive structure; `(a (b c))` is the same as `(a b c)`.

**Variable substitution:** `$name` — value of variable `name`.  `$$name`
gives multiple levels of indirection.  `$n` (a number) gives the nth element
of `$*`.  `$name(i)`, `$name(m-n)`, `$name(m-)` give subscripts (origin 1).

**`$#name`:** Number of elements in variable `name`.  An unset variable has
zero elements.

**`$"name`:** All components of `name` joined with spaces as a single string.
A zero-element variable yields the empty string.

**Command substitution:** `` `{command} `` — rc runs the command and splits its
standard output on characters in `$ifs` into a list.  `` `split{command} ``
uses `split` as the separator string instead of `$ifs`.

**Process substitution:** `<{command}` — runs command asynchronously with its
stdout connected to a pipe; the value is a filename referring to the read end.
`>{command}` — connects stdin to a pipe; value is the write-end filename.
Used for non-linear pipelines, e.g. `cmp <{old} <{new}`.

**Concatenation:** `a^b` — concatenates two operands.  If both have the same
number of components they are concatenated pairwise; otherwise one must have
exactly one component (distributed concatenation).

**Free carets:** rc automatically inserts `^` between adjacent words when `$`,
`'`, or `` ` `` immediately follows a word with no space, or when an unquoted
word immediately follows a quoted word.  So `cc -$flags $stem.c` is equivalent
to `cc -^$flags $stem^.c`.

## I/O redirections

    >file         redirect stdout to file (create/truncate)
    >>file        append stdout to file
    <file         redirect stdin from file
    <>file        open file once for reading and writing (stdin)
    <<eof         here document; variable substitution unless eof is quoted
    >[2]file      redirect fd 2 to file
    >[2=1]        dup fd 1 to fd 2
    >[2=]         close fd 2
    <[3]file      redirect fd 3 from file
    |[fd]         pipe using fd instead of stdout as output end
    |[fd0=fd1]    pipe from fd1 to fd0

Redirections are executed left to right.

## Pipelines and compound commands

    cmd1 | cmd2           stdout of cmd1 → stdin of cmd2
    cmd1 && cmd2          execute cmd2 only if cmd1 exits with null status
    cmd1 || cmd2          execute cmd2 only if cmd1 exits with non-null status
    ! cmd                 invert exit status (null↔non-null)
    @ cmd                 run cmd in a subshell

`|` binds most tightly, then `!` and `@`, then `&&` and `||` (both same
lowest precedence).

## Control structures

**if:**

    if (list) command
    if not command        # else-branch of immediately preceding if(...)command

**for:**

    for(name in arguments) command
    for(name) command     # iterates over $*

**while:**

    while(list) command   # list re-evaluated each iteration; empty list = null status

**switch:**

    switch(argument) {
        case pattern ...
            commands
        case pattern ...
            commands
    }
    # Matches argument against each case's pattern(s) using glob matching.
    # / and first chars of . and .. need not be explicitly matched.

**Braces:**

    { list }             # group commands; alters precedence

**Functions:**

    fn name { list }     # define function; $* set to call arguments
    fn name              # remove function definition

**Note handlers (signal-like):**

    fn sighup  { list }   # called on hangup note
    fn sigint  { list }   # called on interrupt note
    fn sigalrm { list }   # called on alarm note
    fn sigfpe  { list }   # called on floating-point trap note
    fn sigexit { list }   # called when rc is about to exit
    fn sighup             # restore default behavior for sighup

**Prefix assignments:**

    name=value command    # assignment in effect only for the command's duration
                          # (or permanently if command is empty)

## Built-in commands

    .  [-biq] file ...    Execute commands from file. $* is set to remaining
                          args for the duration. -b: compile before running;
                          -i: run interactively; -q: suppress errors.
    builtin cmd ...       Execute cmd using its built-in meaning, ignoring
                          any function of the same name.
    cd [dir]              Change directory to dir (default $home). Searches $cdpath.
    eval [arg ...]        Concatenate args with spaces, read and execute as rc input.
    exec [command ...]    Replace this rc with command (no return).
    exit [status]         Exit with status (default: current $status).
    flag f [+-]           Set (+), clear (-), or test (neither) flag f.
                          f is a single letter matching a command-line flag.
    rfork [nNeEsfFmF]     Become new process group via rfork(2).
                          Default flags: ens.
                            n = RFNAMEG   (copy name space)
                            N = RFCNAMEG  (new clean name space)
                            e = RFENVG    (copy env)
                            E = RFCENVG   (new empty env)
                            s = RFNOTEG   (new note group)
                            f = RFFDG     (copy fd table)
                            F = RFCFDG    (new empty fd table)
                            m = RFNOMNT   (disallow mounts)
    shift [n]             Delete first n (default 1) elements of $*.
    wait [pid]            Wait for pid (or all outstanding) to exit.
    whatis name ...       Print value of name: assignment for variables,
                          definition for functions, 'builtin' for built-ins,
                          full path for executables.
    ~ subject pattern ... Match subject against patterns (glob rules).
                          Sets $status to 0 if any match, 1 otherwise.
                          Patterns are not subject to filename expansion.

## Special variables

    $*       Argument list; saved/restored around . and function calls.
    $apid    PID of most recently started background command.
    $home    Default directory for cd.
    $ifs     Input field separators for `` ` `` substitution (default: space, tab, newline).
    $path    Search path for commands and . command (default: `. /bin`).
    $pid     rc's own process id (set at startup).
    $prompt  Two-element list: interactive prompt and continuation prompt
             (default: `'% ' '	'`).
    $status  Wait message of the last foreground command (empty = success).
             Used by &&, ||, if, while; also the exit status of rc itself.

## Environment

Each non-empty variable is exported as an environment file `/env/varname`.
Multi-value variables use NUL bytes (`\000`) as separators.  Functions are
exported as files named `fn#functionname` containing the rc source.

When rc starts it reads variable and function definitions from the environment.

## Invocation flags

    -c string  Read commands from string instead of a file.
    -s         Print non-null exit status after each simple command.
    -e         Exit if $status is non-null after a simple command.
    -i         Run interactively (prompt, handle interrupts gracefully).
    -I         Force non-interactive mode.
    -l         Read $home/lib/profile on startup (also triggered by argv0
               beginning with -).
    -m initial Read rc's initialization from initial instead of /rc/lib/rcmain.
    -v         Echo input on fd 2 as it is read.
    -x         Print each simple command before executing it (trace).
    -r         Print internal parse tree form of commands as executed (debug).
    -b         Compile whole script before executing (enables full syntax check).
    -p         (no-op)
    -d         (no-op)

## Startup

rc reads `/rc/lib/rcmain` (or the file given with `-m`) for initialization.
With `-l`, `/rc/lib/rcmain.local` and `$home/lib/profile` are sourced first.

## Examples

Simple pipeline:
    ls | grep '\.c$' | wc -l

List variables and for loop:
    files=(a.c b.c c.c)
    for(f in $files) echo $f

If/else:
    if(test -f /tmp/lock) {
        echo locked
    }
    if not
        echo not locked

Function definition and call:
    fn greet {
        echo hello $1
    }
    greet world

Switch:
    switch($1){
    case *.c
        echo C source
    case *.h
        echo header
    case *
        echo unknown
    }

Background job with pid check:
    sleep 10 &
    echo started $apid

Non-linear pipeline (compare outputs of two commands):
    cmp <{old args} <{new args}

Redirect stderr to stdout:
    cmd >[2=1]

Here document (variable substitution active):
    cat << END
    Hello $user
    END

Here document (no substitution — quoted marker):
    cat << 'END'
    Literal $dollar
    END

Capture command output into a variable:
    now=`{date}

Check if a variable matches a pattern (avoiding changing $status via ~):
    if(~ $os plan9) echo 'on plan 9'

Temporary variable for a single command:
    HOME=/tmp cmd

rfork to get a private namespace:
    rfork n
    bind /tmp /bin

## Differences from POSIX sh / bash

**No backslash escaping:** `\` is not a general escape character in rc.
Use single quotes for literal strings.  `\<newline>` is only a line
continuation (treated as whitespace).

**Single quotes, not double:** rc has no double-quoted strings.  `'...'`
is the quoting mechanism; embed a literal `'` as `''`.

**No `$( )` command substitution:** Use `` `{cmd} `` (backtick-brace)
instead of `$(cmd)`.

**Lists, not word splitting:** Variables hold lists of strings natively.
`x=(a b c); echo $x` passes three arguments to echo.  There is no IFS-based
word splitting on substitution; `$ifs` is only used for `` ` `` substitution.

**`^` for concatenation:** Use `a^b` or free-caret insertion instead of
`${a}b` juxtaposition.  `$stem.c` automatically becomes `$stem^.c`.

**`$#var` for list length:** Use `$#var` instead of `${#var}`.  Use `$"var`
to join a list into a space-separated string.

**`if not` instead of `else`:** Chained if-else uses `if not` rather than
`else`.  The `if not` command must immediately follow the corresponding
`if (list) command` — no intervening commands.

**`fn` keyword, not `function`/`()`:** Functions are defined with `fn name {
list }`.  There are no local variables; extra parameters serve as locals.

**`~` for pattern matching:** The `~` built-in matches against glob patterns
(not regexps) without triggering filename expansion.  It sets `$status` to 0
on match.  Note: testing `$status` via `~` changes `$status`.

**`rfork` as a built-in:** Process resource sharing is controlled via `rfork`
with Plan 9 flags, not via POSIX `unshare` or `clone`.  `rfork e` (private
environment) is a common idiom at the top of scripts to avoid polluting the
caller's environment.

**Notes, not signals:** rc handles notes (Plan 9's signal-like mechanism)
via `fn sighup`, `fn sigint`, etc.  The note names and mechanism differ from
POSIX signal names and `trap`.

**`$status` is a string, not a number:** Exit status is a wait message string.
An empty string means success; any non-empty string means failure.  Numeric
exit codes from execed programs are converted to strings like `"status: 1"`.

**No arithmetic:** rc has no arithmetic operators.  Use `awk` or `dc` for
arithmetic.

**No arrays with `[]`:** Lists are the only collection type.  Subscript with
`$name(i)` (1-based origin).

**No `export` built-in:** Variables are automatically exported to the
environment when non-empty.

**No `read` built-in:** Read from a file using `line=\`{sed 1q}` or similar.

**Shell scripts use `/bin/rc`:** The shebang for rc scripts is `#!/bin/rc`,
not `#!/bin/sh`.  `/bin/sh` does not exist on 9front.

**`$path` not `$PATH`:** The search path variable is `$path` (lowercase), a
list.  There is no colon-separated `$PATH`.

**Process substitution syntax:** Uses `<{cmd}` and `>{cmd}` (not `<(cmd)` as
in bash).

**`@` for subshell:** `@ { ... }` runs a subshell; bash uses `( ... )`.

